The patient is a 12-year-old male presenting with new red bumps on the chest, arms, and legs. Among the options, Neurofibromatosis Type I (NF1) is the most likely diagnosis. NF1 is characterized by skin findings such as café-au-lait spots and neurofibromas. While café-au-lait spots are typically flat, neurofibromas can present as raised, red or flesh-colored bumps. These skin manifestations are common in NF1, especially in childhood. 

Ehlers-Danlos Syndrome (A) involves hypermobility and skin elasticity but does not typically cause such bumps. Fragile X Syndrome (B) primarily affects neurodevelopment and lacks skin lesions as a hallmark. Neurofibromatosis Type II (C) is associated with bilateral vestibular schwannomas and fewer skin lesions. Thus, the described red bumps align best with NF1.

